Based on your HTML and the image, the Cancel button is present in the DOM but not visible likely due to either:

1. CSS hiding it


2. *ngIf="editingId" is not truthy


3. Layout constraints (e.g. display, margin, float, etc.)




---

✅ Fix 1: Make Sure editingId Is Set Properly

Ensure editingId is assigned when editing starts. For example:

editRate(rate: any) {
  this.editingId = rate.id; // Make sure 'rate.id' exists and is assigned
  this.form.patchValue(rate);
}


---

✅ Fix 2: Adjust HTML Button Section

Make sure both buttons are styled and inside a proper block layout:

<div class="button-row">
  <button type="submit">
    {{ editingId ? 'Update' : 'Add' }}
  </button>
  <button type="button" (click)="cancelEdit()" *ngIf="editingId">
    Cancel
  </button>
</div>


---

✅ Fix 3: Complete CSS to Display Buttons

Add this to your exchange-rates.component.css or global styles.css:

.button-row {
  display: flex;
  gap: 10px;
  margin-top: 10px;
}

button {
  padding: 6px 12px;
  font-size: 14px;
  background-color: #4CAF50;
  color: white;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 4px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

button[type="button"] {
  background-color: #f44336; /* Red cancel button */
}

button:hover {
  opacity: 0.9;
}


---

✅ Fix 4: Ensure editingId Has a Value

In your .ts:

cancelEdit() {
  this.editingId = null;
  this.form.reset();
}


---

✅ Fix 5: Component Imports (if you're using Angular Material)

Ensure these are in your app.module.ts or imported into your standalone component:

import { CommonModule } from '@angular/common';
import { FormsModule, ReactiveFormsModule } from '@angular/forms';
import { HttpClientModule } from '@angular/common/http';
import { MatInputModule } from '@angular/material/input';
import { MatButtonModule } from '@angular/material/button';
import { MatSelectModule } from '@angular/material/select';
import { MatFormFieldModule } from '@angular/material/form-field';


